 The aforementioned scholar estimated that the combustion of fossil fuels could ultimately emit sufficient carbon dioxide to raise the Earth’s temperature by approximately 5 - 6°C or 9 - 11°F.
 Since then,
 approximately 130 years have passed;
 nevertheless,
 the fundamental physics underlying these calculations has remained unchanged.
 What has evolved are the techniques employed in our projections,
 which have become considerably more detailed and precise 
