\begin_layout Standard
The results summarized in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Statistical-comparison-for"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 indicate that the comparison GENCLASS vs MLP yields 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.0195$
\end_inset

,
 implying a statistically significant difference (
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.05$
\end_inset

) and supporting the conclusion that GENCLASS outperforms MLP under the adopted experimental setting.
 The comparison GENCLASS vs RBF results in 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.2492$
\end_inset

,
 which is not significant (ns,
\begin_inset Formula $p>0.05$
\end_inset

),
 therefore,
 given the available datasets,
 there is insufficient statistical evidence to claim a systematic performance difference between GENCLASS and RBF at the 5% significance level.
 In contrast,
 GENCLASS vs SVM yields 
\begin_inset Formula $p=8.74\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset

,
 an extremely small value (
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.0001$
\end_inset

),
 providing very strong statistical evidence that GENCLASS outperforms SVM on the evaluated datasets.
 The comparison GENCLASS vs NNC produces 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.6583$
\end_inset

 (ns),
 suggesting that no statistically significant difference can be established between GENCLASS and NNC.
 Finally,
 the overall Friedman test reports
\begin_inset Formula $p=2.49\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.0001$
\end_inset

) ,
 confirming that,
 when all models are jointly considered across all datasets,
 there are statistically significant performance differences and the methods cannot be regarded as equivalent.
 Overall,
 these findings substantiate that GENCLASS is decisively and statistically superior to SVM and significantly different from MLP,
 while differences relative to RBF and NNC are not statistically significant under the 
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.05$
\end_inset

 criterion.
\end_layout

