name "subsec:Experiments-with-the"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Table-8-Experimental-results-on-Ng"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 investigates the effect of the number of generations 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

 on the proposed model,
 using classification error percentages as the evaluation metric (lower is better).
 The overall trend is strongly improving with increasing
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

:
 the mean error (AVERAGE) decreases from 4.46% at 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=50 to 1.45% at 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=2000,
 corresponding to a 3.01 percentage-point reduction and an approximate 67.4% relative decrease.
 The gains are not evenly distributed across increments:
 50→100 (-0.99),
 100→200 (-0.82),
 200→1000 (-0.98),
 and 1000→2000 (-0.21),
 indicating diminishing returns beyond 1000 generations,
 where additional computational effort yields smaller improvements in the mean error.
 At the dataset level,
 all regions improve substantially from 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=50 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=2000,
 with the largest relative reductions observed for TURKEY (2.63%→0.37%,
 ~85.9%) and ARABIA (3.03%→0.63%,
 ~79.2%).
 CONGO also improves markedly (14.12%→4.18%,
 ~70.4%) but remains the most challenging dataset across all settings,
 consistently exhibiting the highest errors.
 ICELAND shows the smallest overall relative improvement (4.32%→2.58%,
 ~40.3%) and a slight degradation from 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=1000 to
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

 =2000 (2.47%→2.58%),
 suggesting that for certain datasets additional generations may introduce over-training effects and/or stochastic variability that partially offsets expected gains.
 The slight degradation in the ICELAND dataset between
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

 =1000 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

=2000 can be attributed to stochastic fluctuations in the evolutionary search and dataset\SpecialChar nobreakdash
specific characteristics that limit further improvement beyond a certain number of generations.
 Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

 also reduces cross-dataset variability:
 the maximum error drops from 14.12% to 4.18% and the range (max–min) shrinks from 11.92 to 3.81 percentage points,
 while the standard deviation across datasets decreases from about 4.00 to 1.30,
 supporting a more uniform generalization profile at higher
\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

